---
// Scene 6: Honest Limits
// Readback verdict is weak, corpus-amplitude fails margin
// Ship it clearly, don't hide it
---

<section id="limits" class="section-divider">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <h2>Honest limits: readback is weak, amplitude coupling fails margin</h2>

    <p class="text-lg">
      The entire program prioritizes statistical rigor as a pruning mechanism, not a blessing mechanism.
      Some things work. Some don't. Both are findings.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-orange-50 dark:bg-orange-950 border-2 border-orange-300 dark:border-orange-700 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
      <h3 class="font-serif text-xl mb-4">Negative 1: Readback verification is weak</h3>

      <p>
        The āgama re-cognition test: does the model take a written concept suggestion? Measured as
        the rank of that concept in the next generation's output probability distribution (top-M acceptance).
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-6">
        <div>
          <div class="text-sm text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-300 uppercase font-semibold mb-2">Achieved</div>
          <div class="text-3xl font-serif font-semibold">BA ≈ 0.59</div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">
            Balanced accuracy on held-out test corpus (n=120)
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="text-sm text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-300 uppercase font-semibold mb-2">Threshold</div>
          <div class="text-3xl font-serif font-semibold">0.60</div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">
            Minimum bar for a load-bearing readback claim
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        <strong>Interpretation:</strong> Readback verification exists but is marginally insufficient as a
        confidence test. It can't carry claims about what the model "understood." We don't use it as evidence.
      </p>

      <div class="text-xs text-muted mt-4">
        <strong>Gates:</strong> gate_L14_readback_sweep (36-setting search, screen-exploratory) ·
        gate_L15_readback_holdout (held-out replication)
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-orange-50 dark:bg-orange-950 border-2 border-orange-300 dark:border-orange-700 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-serif text-xl mb-4">Negative 2: Corpus-amplitude coupling fails strict margin</h3>

      <p>
        Hypothesis: does steering lift scale monotonically with concept similarity to the training corpus?
        A dose-response curve is expected if workspace content is corpus-learned.
      </p>

      <p class="mt-4">
        <strong>Result:</strong> Direction confirmed (higher corpus overlap → higher lift). But magnitude
        fails the pre-registered margin (effect size d ≈ 0.3, threshold ≥ 0.5).
      </p>

      <div class="text-sm mt-4 p-3 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800">
        <div class="text-xs text-muted uppercase font-semibold">Disposition</div>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm">
          Not a refutation—a downgrade. The effect is real (sign-consistent) but smaller than the
          registered bar. We report it by sign-consistency, not by claiming a confirmed margin.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="text-xs text-muted mt-4">
        <strong>Gate:</strong> gate_L19_corpus_amplitude (fail-on-margin)
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-6 rounded mt-8">
      <h3 class="font-serif text-lg mb-3">Why ship honest negatives?</h3>

      <p>
        <strong>Epistemology:</strong> The goal is understanding and steering of LLMs, not winning a grant.
        A weak readback metric tells you something real: steering works without readback verification being
        tight. That's interesting. It says the mechanism is NOT "write, then verify write was received."
      </p>

      <p class="mt-4">
        <strong>Engineering:</strong> You can't build a reliable system on a soft metric. If readback were
        a critical path, the paper would be misleading. It isn't, so we say so.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
